recordings.rmk:
Bird: Size about pipit as is build. Light greenish in color head and below (back to vent) with slight streaking on breast. Large vireo looking bill but sharp, gray with a darker top bill. No noticeable eye-ring. Darker faint black wings and tail with pale wing-bars. Legs gray.

When called with a Scarlet Tanager chip the bird came down into bushes in front of me about 10ft and chipped at me.  I thing this was an female Scarlet Tanager.

I'm also curious what you think the vireo singing at the end it.  I think it is a yellow-throated vireo.

Thanks,
Gary

recordings.file-name: XC388144-171001_1619 LEFL peep XC Zamorano ecotrail HN by Oliver Komar.MP3
recordings.rmk: This bright peep call is not a call I frequently recognize for Empidonax minimus (which is common at this site and around my home). At first I suspected it was an Empidonax flaviventris. However, either the same or a different bird was giving the same call shortly after I made this cut, and I located it and observed it to have Least Flycatcher field marks. It also gave the dry chebek call and a few of the softer, characteristic whit calls. I posted that recording to eBird/Macaulay Library (https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/70529031).

recordings.loc: South side of Whitesand Lake, Saskatchewan
recordings.rmk:
Flight songs from several individuals as well as perched songs and calls.  Flight songs from ~ 0:00 to 0:04, 0:08 to 0:12, and 0:47 to 0:51. Recorded in trembling aspen (Populus tremuloides) forest, at dusk, on iPhone with internal mic. 

Flight songs are given regularly in this area around dawn and dusk, and often appear to be given in clusters, with a flight song of one bird closely followed by nearby birds giving flight songs as well, with several nearby birds often giving flight songs simultaneously.  In flight songs, birds launch themselves upwards from the aspen canopy, typically gaining ~5 metres of height above the canopy and remaining airborne and vocal for several seconds.  Immediately prior to flight songs, birds are typically perched in the aspen canopy giving regular-paced "chebek, chebek..." song.   As the birds take flight the delivery of the "chebek" phrases becomes more rapid, and the "chebek" phrases become interspersed with "beert" phrases, and occasionally "whit" or "brrt" phrases, for the course of the flight song.

recordings.loc: North side of Whitesand Lake, Saskatchewan
recordings.rmk:
Two flight songs given by Least Flycatchers at dusk; both are followed by narration indicating the flight songs.  

Recorded at trembling aspen (Populus tremuloides) forest edge, at dusk, on iPhone with external mic.  Multiple perched birds were singing and calling in the vicinity as well.   

Flight songs are given regularly in this area around dawn and dusk, and often appear to be given in clusters, with a flight song of one bird closely followed by nearby birds giving flight songs as well, with several nearby birds often giving flight songs simultaneously.  In flight songs, birds launch themselves upwards from the aspen canopy, typically gaining ~5 metres of height above the canopy and remaining airborne and vocal for several seconds.  Immediately prior to flight songs, birds are typically perched in the aspen canopy giving regular-paced "chebek, chebek..." song; as the birds take flight, the delivery of the "chebek" phrases becomes more rapid and the "chebek" phrases become interspersed with "beert" phrases for the course of the flight song.  Some flight songs were heard to include occasional "whit" and "brrt" phrases as well as the more common "chebek" and "beert" phrases given in rapid succession.
